{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_01QjNkMLJNhbZNCk1ZU9JHMB","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a comprehensive understanding of the codebase. Let me plan and implement the requirements drafting feature. This is a large implementation with many files to create/modify. Let me use the TodoWrite tool to track progress and then start implementing.\n\nKey architectural decisions:\n1. **Generalize agent_execution** - Need to make `InvocationRequest` accept a domain-neutral contract instead of only `StageContract`. I'll introduce a trait `StructuredContract` that both `StageContract` and the new requirements contracts implement.\n2. **Requirements model** - `RequirementsRun` state at `.ralph-burning/requirements/<run-id>/run.json`\n\n\n3. **Requirements contracts** - Four new contracts: question_set, requirements_draft, requirements_review, project_seed\n4. **Requirements service** - Orchestrates the full lifecycle\n5. **Filesystem stores** - For requirements runs\n6. **CLI handlers** - Wire up the four commands\n7. **Tests** - Unit tests and Gherkin scenarios\n\nNow I need to tackle the core coupling issue: `InvocationRequest` currently expects a `StageContract`, but I need it to work with multiple contract types. The key integration points are `AgentExecutionPort::check_capability` which takes `&StageContract`, and the error handling that depends on this type. I'll need to refactor these to use the new trait abstraction. use `StageId` from the stage contract.\n\nFor the generalization, I think the cleanest approach is:\n1. Create a `StructuredContract` trait in agent_execution that abstracts evaluation\n2. Make `StageContract` implement it\n3. Create requirements-specific contracts that also implement it\n4. Update `InvocationRequest` to use a boxed trait or enum\n\nActually, looking more carefully at the code, the coupling is:\n- `InvocationRequest.stage_contract: StageContract` - used for:\n  - `request.stage_contract.evaluate_permissive()` in service.rs\n  - `request.stage_contract.stage_id` for error reporting\n  - Passed to `check_capability` \n  - Used in stub_backend for payload lookup\n\nThe spec says the agent_execution module needs to move away from workflow-specific `StageContract` usage toward a domain-neutral structured-contract interface. I'm thinking an enum might work, but a trait is probably cleaner since `StageContract` is already used across multiple places—in the invocation request itself, passed to capability checks, called for evaluation, and referenced for stage IDs in error handling and payload lookups. A trait would let me define the minimal interface needed without forcing all these call sites to change. I'm realizing the core issue: requirements contracts need their own identity separate from the `StageId` enum to avoid coupling them to the workflow. The minimal fix is to create a generalized contract identifier type and update the error handling to work with either stage-based or requirements-based contracts, keeping the two systems decoupled.\n\nDefining the contract types...\n\nActually, I'm realizing the key insight here—`AgentExecutionService` doesn't actually need the full validated payload from contract evaluation, it just needs to know whether validation succeeded or failed. The actual `ValidatedBundle` with its workflow-specific payload gets consumed by the caller, not by the agent execution layer itself, so I can simplify the trait to only return validation results without worrying about the payload type.\n\nI'm introducing a trait that captures what agent execution actually needs: a contract ID for error reporting and a validation method that returns a simple `Result<(), ContractError>`. Then I need to decide whether to update the error variants to use `ContractId` instead of `StageId` for consistency, or find another approach.\n\nLooking at the error types, they're all currently keyed by `StageId` — things like `InvocationFailed`, `InvocationTimeout`, and `ContractError::SchemaValidation`. Changing all of these to use `ContractId` would be too invasive and break existing tests, so I'll keep the errors using string-based identification for the contract dimension instead.\n\nThe simplest approach is to avoid modifying the error types altogether. I can create a `DomainContract` enum in agent_execution that wraps either a `StageContract` or a `RequirementsContract`, then have the requirements service handle its own validation before and after calling agent_execution, while agent_execution just does the raw invocation without contract validation for requirements. The spec says requirements contracts don't need to be added to the project workflow `StageId` enum, so I need to re-read it carefully to understand the exact constraints.\n\nLooking at what the requirements service actually needs from agent_execution—resolving the backend target, invoking it with a prompt, validating the response, and handling timeouts—the pragmatic solution is to make `InvocationRequest` more generic by accepting a boxed contract type instead of being tightly coupled to `StageId`. I'm realizing that boxing trait objects won't work since `InvocationRequest` needs to derive `Clone`, and trait objects can't be cloned. So instead I'll use an enum wrapper that holds either a `StageContract` or `RequirementsContract`, implementing the necessary methods on the enum itself to handle both variants.\n\nBut this creates a circular dependency problem—requirements_drafting depends on agent_execution, so if agent_execution's enum includes `RequirementsContract`, then agent_execution would depend back on requirements_drafting. I need to break this cycle by defining a shared contract trait that both modules can implement independently, rather than coupling them through an enum or trait object in one place.\n\nActually, the most straightforward solution is to just make `stage_contract` optional in `InvocationRequest` and handle validation more generically, avoiding the need for complex abstraction altogether.\n\nLooking at how `AgentExecutionService::invoke` actually uses the contract—it only calls `evaluate_permissive` on the payload and checks if the backend supports the stage. The requirements service could handle its own validation separately without needing to fit into the same contract framework, so I could define a `ContractId` enum that distinguishes between stage-based and requirements-based contracts...\n\nDefining the contract ID enum... I'm going back and forth on the design here, but I need to commit to something. Let me settle on creating a generic contract wrapper in the agent_execution model that uses a unified ContractId enum with variants for different contract types, and I'll implement a Display trait to format the identifiers appropriately.\n\nThen I'm modifying InvocationRequest to include both the contract_id for tracking and an optional stage_contract for workflow invocations, with validation only running when the stage_contract is present. The requirements service will handle its own contract validation separately after receiving the envelope back.\n\nStill working through the error type handling...\n\nActually, I'm going to step back and take a different approach. The key insight is that ContractError already has a stage_id field, and for requirements we don't need StageId at all since we have our own identifiers. The real goal here is to decouple agent_execution from the workflow-specific StageContract so it can work with any structured contract interface.\n\nDefining a trait-based approach...\n\nActually, wait—ContractError uses StageId, so if I want a domain-neutral contract, I either need a different error type or to modify ContractError itself. But changing existing interfaces breaks things.\n\nLet me go with the simplest solution: use an enum that can hold either a StageContract or a custom contract with a label and validation function...\n\nDef